  "datePublished": "2026-03-04",
  "description": "Observer bias occurs when personal preference, experience, or access shapes what gets recorded. It is a dominant driver of iNaturalist data structure.\n¶Indicators Overrepresentation of charismatic taxa. High-density records in easily accessible parks. Skewed seasonal patterns driven by human schedules. Repeated sampling of the same “favorite” sites without documenting effort. ¶Mitigation practices Intentionally observe under-recorded taxa. Balance urban observations with less accessible habitats when possible. Document effort to help data users model bias. Add notes when sampling is intentionally opportunistic vs. structured. Contribute to projects that encourage standardized effort (bioblitzes with protocols, repeated surveys). ¶What goes wrong if you do this poorly Observer bias creates misleading distribution patterns and weakens ecological inference, especially for rare or inconspicuous species. The resulting data can look dense while still being ecologically incomplete.\n",
  "name": "Failure mode: observer bias",
  "publisher": {
